The Telegraph - Calcutta : International

 Korea agrees to nuke talks

 Beijing, Oct. 31 (Reuters): North Korea agreed today to return to six-party talks on dismantling its atomic weapons just weeks after staging its first nuclear test, and a US envoy said he wanted to see substantial progress after a year-long hiatus.

 Envoys from North Korea, the US and China met in Beijing and agreed to resume the talks in the near future, the Chinese foreign ministry said on its website.

 After the breakthrough meeting, US assistant secretary of state Christopher Hill said in Beijing that he expected rapid progress from the next talks but acknowledged that fully settling the nuclear standoff was likely to be painstaking. 

